10.2.3: Composition: Object References as Memebers of Classes:¶

Each Account has a name, and a Account has a balance. In order for an object to exist as an object in python, the attributes are refeerences to objects of other classes. In this case an Account object's name attribute is a reference to a string object an an Accounts Object's balance attribute is a reference to a Decimal. In short, by embedding references to objects of other types is known as composition, meaning that there is an established relationship between the attributes of the object and the class it is in.

10.3: Controlling Access to Attributes:¶

Class Account's methods validate their arguments to ensure that the balance is always valid. Attributes name and balance only to get the values of those attributes, but we can also use those attributes to modify their values.

In [14]:
account1 = Account('John Green', Decimal('50.00'))
In [15]:
account1.balance
Out[15]:
Decimal('50.00')
In [16]:
account1.balance = Decimal('-1000.00')
In [17]:
account1.balance
Out[17]:
Decimal('-1000.00')

Unlike methods, data attributes cannot validate values assigned to them. A classe's client code allows for the encapsulation of an object's data from the client code. In a sense creating privet data.

In [49]:

In [50]:

In [51]:

In [52]:

In [53]:
figure, axes_list = plt.subplots(nrows=4, ncols=13)

figure.set_figwidth(16)
figure.set_figheight(9)

for axes in axes_list.ravel():
    axes.get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
    axes.get_yaxis().set_visible(False)
    image_name = deck_of_cards.deal_card().image_name
    img = mpimg.imread(str(path.joinpath(image_name).resolve()))
    axes.imshow(img)

figure.tight_layout()

10.8.3 Processing Commission & Salaried Employees:¶

Inheritance allows every object of a subclass to be trated as an object of that subclasse's base class. We can place objects related through inhertitance into a list, then iterate through the list and treat each element as a base-class object. Allowing for objects to be process in a general way/

In [80]:
employees = [c, s]

for employee in employees:
    print(employee)
    print(f'{employee.earnings():,.2f}\n')

social security number: 333-33-3333
gross sales: 20000.00
commission rate: 0.06
1,200.00

social security number: 444-44-4444
gross sales: 10000.00
commission rate: 0.04
base salary: 300.00

10.9: Duck Typing & Polymorphism:¶

Duck typing allows for professing an object at execution time, its type doesn't matter, as long as the data attribute, property or method desired is accessable.

In [2]:
class WellPaidDuck:
    def _repr_(self):
        return 'I am a well-paid duck'
    def earnings(self):
        return Decimal('1_000_000.00')
In [3]:
from decimal import Decimal
In [5]:
from salariedcommissionemployee import SalariedCommissionEmployee
In [13]:
c = CommissionEmployee('Sue', 'Jones', '333-33-3333',
                      Decimal('10000.00'), Decimal('0.06'))
In [9]:
s = SalariedCommissionEmployee('Bob', 'Lewis', '444-44-4444',
                              Decimal('5000.00'), Decimal('0.04'), Decimal('300.00'))
In [10]:
d = WellPaidDuck()
In [14]:
employees = [c, s, d]

10.14: Unit Testing with Docstrings and doctest:¶

We can use the doctest module to help test code and conveniently retest if after you make modifications. The testmod function, inspects your functions', methods' and classes' docstrings looking for sample Python statments proceeded by >>>, each followed on the next line by the given statemetn's expected output.

Trying: account1 = Account('John Green', Decimal('50.00')) Expecting nothing ok Trying: account1.name Expecting: 'John Green' ok Trying: account1.balance Expecting: Decimal('50.00') ok Trying: account2 = Account('John Green', Decimal('-50.00')) Expecting: Traceback (most recent call last): ... ValueError: Initial balance must be >= to 0.00. ok 3 items had no tests: main main.Account main.Account.deposit 1 items passed all tests: 4 tests in main.Account.init 4 tests in 4 items. 4 passed and 0 failed. Test passed.
